   "user": "O_oNevermore",
   "message": "the pitch I gave some guy asking what I'm working on:\n\nI grew up Christian and became atheist rationalist (specifically critrat) and then went into effective altruism and also I discovered tpot mystics \n\nso I have essentially 4 different cultures inside of me and they conflict with one another\n\nso I set out initially to create a bridge between the rationalists and the mystics/religious through philosophical means, essentially trying to work on the cultural repos rather than my own personal repos\n\nand I think Tom Hyde's very recent and incomplete stance called wonderism provides the first true philosophical bridge that achieves what I wanted to achieve. he tries to reconcile the Romantic movement and Enlightenment Rationalism which are currently considered adversaries \n\nso I adopted the identity of a \"romantic rationalist\" because I am trying to extend Tom Hyde's wonderism way further than he would himself take it\n\nthe core idea is simple, axiology (the study of value, what is good, what is important) precedes things like ethics and aesthetics (and forms an unexplored part of epistemology)\n\n.",
   "timestamp": "2026-07-17T11:38:51.047000+00:00",
   "channel": "✍️eval-log",
   "thread": null,
   "reply_to": null,
   "id": "discord:1527640725062422578",
   "user_id": "discord:335107602243518466",
   "url": "https://discord.com/channels/1344300408893345863/1409673828673523762/1527640725062422578",
   "attachments": [],
   "platform": "discord",
   "server": "ORI 1.0 (2025)"
  },
  {
   "user": "O_oNevermore",
   "message": "the core problem today is the two camps have different value schemas (a concept I created)\n\nthe first schema is:\n\nemotion > logic\n\nthis represents the religious, mystics and romantics (you can replace emotion with intuition or romance or whatever, and logic with reason, science, rigor or whatever)\n\none is more important than the other, in art, in ethics, in epistemology etc\n\nthe second schema is:\n\nlogic > emotion\n\nthis represents the rationalists\n\nso that is the core conflict, it's not really a conflict of theories or ideas it's a conflict of values, if you value emotion or intuition enough then you can \"take stories (or feelings etc) seriously\" in the same way you can take ideas or theories seriously, so it resolves a lot of the disputes\n\nromantic rationalism has this schema:\n\nemotions == logic\n\nthey are equally important, like electricity and magnitism, they unify to make the electromagnetic force\n\nI currently believe value schemas are a unifying concept in various fields of philosophy including aesthetics, ethics, memetics, comparative culture and comparative art/literature, phenomenology\n\nI think of it like interpretability research, where cultures and religions and works of art etc are black boxes that you can open using the tool of the value schema, you can analyze utterances, and rather than comparing the concepts (which is impossible because they use different sign systems entirely) you compare the value schemas encoded in their speech\n\ne.g. a Daoist says the Dao that can be named is not the true Dao, and when you speak to one they will tell you that you value words too much\n\nfrom that it's clear there is a value structure there and it's clear that this value structure conflicts with e.g. Christianity's emphasis on the Word and definitely with the rationalists (commonly mockingly called wrodcels)\n\nfinding the value structure allows you to compare it to other religions and make sense",
   "timestamp": "2026-07-17T11:39:03.560000+00:00",
   "channel": "✍️eval-log",
   "thread": null,
   "reply_to": null,
   "id": "discord:1527640777545486427",
   "user_id": "discord:335107602243518466",
   "url": "https://discord.com/channels/1344300408893345863/1409673828673523762/1527640777545486427",
   "attachments": [],
   "platform": "discord",
   "server": "ORI 1.0 (2025)"
  },
  {
   "user": "O_oNevermore",
   "message": ".\n\nanyway, currently I'm just building a site that is kinds like substack and Google docs combined, there I will put my position into words more completely\n\nI've written some stuff already, on my substack there is an article of being and becoming (the human condition) that shows how I use value structures to compare literature and religions, but I'd like to take that further and make it empirical with things like implicit association tests, which use reaction time to measure your schemas (I'm making a site that allows you to make arbitrary implicit association tests)\n\nbut this is way more than I can chew and my interests extend beyond what I mentioned so progress is slow",
